# Java Servlet Project Explanation (ServletProject_1)

## 🔷 Project Overview

This is a **Maven-based Java Servlet Web Application**.
It demonstrates how a client (browser) sends a request and the servlet processes it and sends a response back.

---

## 🔷 Project Structure

ServletProject_1
│
├── src/main/java
│   └── com.sub.nit
│       └── MyServlet.java (Servlet Class)
│
├── src/main/webapp
│   ├── META-INF
│   ├── WEB-INF
│   │   ├── lib
│   │   └── web.xml (Servlet Configuration)
│   └── index.html (Frontend Page)
│
├── target (Compiled Files)
├── pom.xml (Maven Configuration)

---

## 🔷 Components Explanation

### 1. MyServlet.java

* Located in: src/main/java/com.sub.nit
* This is the **main servlet class**
* It extends HttpServlet
* Contains service() method to handle requests

Example:
System.out.println("I am in Service Method");

* It processes request and sends response using PrintWriter

---

### 2. index.html

* Located in: src/main/webapp
* This is the **first webpage (UI)**
* Opens when project runs

---

### 3. web.xml

* Located in: WEB-INF
* Used for **servlet mapping**

Example: <servlet> <servlet-name>my</servlet-name> <servlet-class>com.sub.nit.MyServlet</servlet-class> </servlet>

<servlet-mapping>
    <servlet-name>my</servlet-name>
    <url-pattern>/test</url-pattern>
</servlet-mapping>

* Connects browser request → servlet class

---

### 4. pom.xml

* Maven configuration file
* Contains dependencies like Servlet API

---

## 🔷 Working Flow of Project

1. User runs the project on server (Tomcat)
2. index.html page opens in browser
3. User sends request (via URL or link)
4. web.xml maps request to MyServlet
5. service() method executes
6. Servlet processes request
7. Response is sent back to browser

---

## 🔷 Key Concepts Used

* Servlet API
* HttpServlet
* Request & Response handling
* PrintWriter
* Web.xml mapping
* Maven project structure

---

